@Node "FFRI" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/FFRI"
@Next "FFRClear"
@Prev "License"
@Toc "Main"

Initialize the index file database.
***********************************

   Usage: FFRI <config> [VERBOSE]

   FFRI creates an index file for FFRS in <DATAPATH>. This index will be
searched first before FFRS begins a search on the harddrive. If a file
is not found in the index, FFRS will continue searching on your HD (as
it used to do) or in the case of the keyword INDEXONLY will stop the
search.

   If you have xpk installed and specify CRUNCHMODE in FFRS.cfg, the
index is crunched using the specified compressor.

   The commandline option VERBOSE prints out more detailed informations.


@EndNode

@Node "IndexFind" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/IndexFind"
@Next "DateDir"
@Prev "FFRStat"
@Toc "Main"

Find a file in the index file.
******************************

   Usage: IndexFind DATAPATH/A PATTERN/A NOFANCY/A

   Indexfind locates single files or files matching a pattern in the
FFRS index. If you specify NOFANCY, Indexfind just displays the
filename with complete path.

   Indexfind returns RETURN_WARN (5) if no file has been found.


@EndNode

@Node "FFRClear" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/FFRClear"
@Next "FFRKill"
@Prev "FFRI"
@Toc "Main"

Reseting the 24h limit request.
*******************************

   FFRClear - Reset the 24h request limit for a given node.

   Usage: FFRClear Address/K,All/S

   The 24h limits will be reset to zero.


@EndNode

@Node "FFRKill" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/FFRKill"
@Next "FFRStat"
@Prev "FFRClear"
@Toc "Main"

Kill all/partial accounting data.
*********************************

   FFRKill - Delete the accounting data of a given node.

   Usage: FFRKill Address/K,All/S:

   All accounting data will be deleted for a given node address.


@EndNode

@Node "FFRStat" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/FFRStat"
@Next "IndexFind"
@Prev "FFRKill"
@Toc "Main"

List accounting statistic.
**************************

   FFRStat - List accounting data of all nodes.

   Usage: FFRStat

   Try yourself.


@EndNode

@Node "DateDir" "FFRS_Utilities.guide/DateDir"
@Next "Tables of Contents"
@Prev "IndexFind"
@Toc "Main"

DateDir.
********

   Usage: DateDir <path>

   DateDir is a simple dir-alike command that also lists UN*X
timestamps in decimal notation. Useful for update requests.


@EndNode

